				<div class="post-alt blog" id="post-2828">
		
					<a href="http://blog.keia.org/2013/12/jang-song-taeks-public-purge-from-north-korean-leadership/" title="Jang Song Taek’s Public Purge from North Korean Leadership"><img src="https://i2.wp.com/blog.keia.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Exit-by-Felix42-contra-la-censura-100x57.jpg" alt=""  width="100"  height="57"  class="woo-image th" /></a>                    
											
					<h2><a title="Permanent Link to Jang Song Taek’s Public Purge from North Korean Leadership" href="http://blog.keia.org/2013/12/jang-song-taeks-public-purge-from-north-korean-leadership/" rel="bookmark">Jang Song Taek’s Public Purge from North Korean Leadership</a></h2>
					<p class="post_date">Posted on 10 December 2013. <span class="singletags">Tags: <a href="http://blog.keia.org/tag/kim-jong-un/" rel="tag">Kim Jong-un</a>, <a href="http://blog.keia.org/tag/leadership-transition/" rel="tag">leadership transition</a>, <a href="http://blog.keia.org/tag/succession/" rel="tag">succession</a></span></p>
		
					<div class="entry">
						<p>Whether Kim Jong-un is in charge or is in trouble after the purge of Jang Song Taek, both possibilities present problems for the U.S. and its allies, demonstrating once again why North Korea is seen as the land of no good options. </p>
							<p><span class="continue"><a title="Permalink to  Jang Song Taek’s Public Purge from North Korean Leadership" href="http://blog.keia.org/2013/12/jang-song-taeks-public-purge-from-north-korean-leadership/">Read the full story</a></span></p>
											</div>
		
